]]:||O2=GRZq}}\n{{BS3||fSTR|O2=MSTRq|O22=RP2oq|||Drake Rd.||}}\n{{BS3||fTEEl|fCONTfq|||to Arlington Reservoir Area|O2=fSTR}}\n{{BS3||fHST|||Site of B&M's Arlington Heights station||}}\n{{BS3|fENDEa|O1=RP2q|RP2q|O2=lhMSTRae|O22=fSTR|RP2w||Park Ave.||}}\n{{BS3|fSTRl|fTEEr}}\n{{BS3||RP2q|O2=fSTR|||Lowell St.||}}\n{{BS3||RP2q|O2=lhMSTRae|O22=fSTR|||Forest St.||}}\n{{BS3|lENDE@Fq|fKRZ|lENDE@Gq||Ryder St.||}}\n{{BS3||fTEEl|fSTR+r||Site of B&M's Brattles station||}}\n{{BS3||RP2q|O2=lhMSTRae|O22=fSTR|fENDEe|O3=RP2q||Brattle St.||}}\n{{BS3||RP2q|O2=lhMSTRae|O22=fSTR|||Grove St.||}}\n{{BS3||fHST|||Site of B&M's [[Arlington Centre (MBTA station)|Arlington Centre station]]||}}\n{{BS3||fSTR|O2=RP4q|||Massachusetts Ave. ([[U.S. Route 3]])||}}\n{{BS3|fSTR+l|fTEEr|||Spy Pond Field}}\n{{BS3|fWBANKl|lDSTR|O2=fSTR|||[[Spy Pond]]|||}}\n{{BS3|fENDEe|O1=RP2q|RP2q|O2=fSTR|||Linwood St.||}}\n{{BS3||fHST|||Site of B&M's [[Lake Street (MBTA Lexington Branch station)|Lake St. station]]||}}\n{{BS3||RP2q|O2=fSTR|||Lake Street||}}\n{{BS3||fTEEl|fCONTfq|||to [[Alewife Brook Greenway]]|O2=fSTR}}\n{{BS3|RP4e|fSTR|O2=MSTRq|O22=RP4oq|RP4w||[[Massachusetts Route 2]]||}}\n{{BS3||fSTR||||in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]]:||O2=GRZq}}\n{{BS3|fCONTgq|fTEEr||||to [[Fitchburg Cutoff Path]]|O2=fSTR}}\n{{BS3||fTEEl|fCONTfq|||to [[Alewife Linear Park]]|O2=fSTR}}\n{{BS3||fKBHFe|O2=utKHSTa|||[[Alewife (MBTA station)|Alewife station]]||}}\n{{BS|utCONTf|||[[Red Line (MBTA)|MBTA Red Line]]}}\n|}\n|}\n\nThe '''Minuteman Bikeway''' is a 10-mile (16-kilometre)<ref>Some sources list it erroneously as 11 miles.  The confusion arises because the mile marker at the beginning of the trail in Bedford is 1 instead of 0.  Wikipedia editors have measured the distance as shown on maps and in Google Earth, and it appears to be 10 miles to within a few hundredths of a mile. For further verification, see: [http://www.pps.org/great_public_spaces/one?public_place_id=18 Project for Public Spaces] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060719234246/http://www.pps.org/great_public_spaces/one?public_place_id=18 |date=2006-07-19 }} or [http://www.bedforddepot.org/history/index.html About the Lexington Branch]</ref> paved multi-use [[rail trail]] located in the [[Greater Boston]] area of [[Massachusetts]]. It runs from [[Bedford, Massachusetts|Bedford]] to [[Alewife (MBTA station)|Alewife station]], at the northern end of the [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red Line]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], passing through the towns of [[Lexington, Massachusetts|Lexington]] and [[Arlington, Massachusetts|Arlington]] along the way. Also along the route are several notable regional sites, including [[Alewife Brook Reservation]], [[Spy Pond]], \"[[Arlington\u2019s Great Meadows]]\" (actually located in Lexington), [[Lexington Battle Green|the Battle Green in Lexington]], and [[Hanscom Air Force Base]].\n\nAt its Cambridge terminus, the bikeway connects with four other bike paths: \n*the [[Fitchburg Cutoff Path]] \n*the [[Cambridge Linear Park]] which, in turn, leads to the [[Somerville Community Path]]. \n*the Alewife Brook Greenway, a connection to the [[Mystic River]] bike path, following [[Alewife Brook]].<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Town of Arlington, MA |url=http://www.arlingtonma.gov/public_documents/ArlingtonMA_DPW/projects/greenway/index |title=Alewife Brook Greenway Corridor Improvement Project |date=July 11, 2012 |accessdate=2013-08-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120721162544/http://www.arlingtonma.gov/public_documents/ArlingtonMA_DPW/projects/greenway/index |archivedate=July 21, 2012 }}</ref> The Alewife Brook extension received $4M from the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]] as the \"Minuteman Bikepath Connector\" project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content/releases/pr021010_ARRA&sid=release|title=Patrick-Murray Administration Obligates 100% of ARRA Highway Funding One Month Ahead of Schedule|date=2010-02-10|accessdate=2010-03-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216235118/http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content%2Freleases%2Fpr021010_ARRA&sid=release|archivedate=2010-02-16}}</ref>\n* a sidewalk path to [[Fresh Pond (Cambridge, Massachusetts)|Fresh Pond Reservation]].\n\nPlans are underway to extend the Somerville Community Path to downtown [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], which would create a much larger continuous bikeway accessible from the Minuteman.\n\nAt the Bedford end, the Minuteman Bikeway connects with the [[Narrow Gauge Rail Trail]] and the [[Reformatory Branch Rail Trail]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bedforddepot.org/railtrails/index.html|title=Rail-Trails at Bedford Depot Park|website=www.bedforddepot.org}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n[[File:Topographic maps of Arlington, Belmont, Lexington Massachusetts 1946.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Map from 1946, where Boston & Maine Railroad (B&M) passes along the route of today's Minuteman Bikeway]]\n\nThe path comprising the current Minuteman Bikeway has a long history. The trail closely approximates the route that [[Paul Revere]] took on his famous ride in 1775, which heralded the beginning of the American Revolution.\n\nAlong the way to becoming a railroad, the path's [[right-of-way (transportation)|right-of-way]] was laid out east of Lexington in 1846 by the [[Lexington and West Cambridge Railroad]] and west of Lexington in 1873 by the [[Middlesex Central Railroad]].\n\n[[Railbanking]] of the line was first proposed in 1974, three years before passenger rail service was discontinued, and a full seven years before rail service was discontinued altogether (in 1981). In 1991, the final plan for the conversion was approved, and construction started on the original section of the bikeway. The path was dedicated in 1992 and completed the following year.<ref name=\"viser2007\"/>\n\nIn 1998 the bikeway was extended from East Arlington to Alewife station (in Cambridge). In 2002 it was repaved in Arlington and in 2004 the Bedford Depot Park Enhancement Project was completed at its western terminus.<ref name=\"viser2007\">Viser, Matt (2007), \"Rage on the bikeway\", The Boston Globe, Volume 272, Number 1, 2007-07-01, p.A1.</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the bikeway was the fifth inductee into the national Rail-Trail Hall of Fame by the Rails-to-Trails Conservancy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minutemanbikeway.org/Pages/HallofFame.html|title=Bikeway-Hall of Fame|website=www.minutemanbikeway.org}}</ref>\n\nThe property is currently owned by the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] and leased to the municipalities through which it passes on an interim basis.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} The MBTA at one point planned to use this right-of-way to extend the [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red Line]] to Arlington Center and Arlington Heights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boston.curbed.com/archives/2014/02/the-red-line-stops-in-arlington-and-lexington.php|title=The Red Line Stops in Arlington and Lexington|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in Spring 2015, the crossing of the path through Arlington Center is expected to be rebuilt to be less discontinuous.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtonma.gov/home/showdocument?id=22444|title=Project Update: September 25, 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.arlingtonma.gov/home/showdocument?id=2932 Map of Preferred Alternative] - Arlington Center Safe Travel Project, March 21, 2013</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nArea residents use the bikeway for a host of activities, including [[cycling|bicycling]], walking, [[jogging]], and [[inline skates|inline skating]]. The main use of the path, however, is for casual biking.<ref name=\"viser2007\"/> In the winter there is often enough snow on the bikeway for [[cross-country skiing]].  However, it is now plowed from Alewife Station to Bedford.<ref name=\"gilsdorf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2008/06/29/popular_bike_trail_gets_even_better/?page=2|title=Popular bike trail gets even better|last=Gilsdorf |first=Ethan|date=June 29, 2008|publisher=boston.com|accessdate=2009-06-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2010/01/24/on_minuteman_bikeway_in_winter_beginning_to_see_their_way_clear/|title=On winter\u2019s path, seeing their way clear|first=Brock|last=Parker|date=24 January 2010|publisher=|via=The Boston Globe}}</ref> No motorized vehicles are allowed except for powered [[wheelchair]]s and emergency vehicles.\n\n==Future possibilities==\n\nNew connections under contemplation include one from Lexington to the Battle Road Trail and one to the [[Charles River]] bike path via Fresh Pond Reservation and the abandoned [[Watertown Branch Railroad]]. A portion of the latter path, at the Watertown end, has been completed and design work on the remaining section to Cambridge is expected to be finished in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mass.gov/eea/docs/dcr/news/public-meetings/materials/projects/2015-11-30-watertown-cambridge-presentation-c.pdf |title=Data|website=www.mass.gov|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, state officials announced that the Somerville Community Path would be extended alongside the [[Green Line Extension]], creating a continuous 4.5 mile route from the Minuteman Bikeway to Boston\u2019s [[Charles River Bike Path]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Conway|first=Abby Elizabeth|title=Somerville Bike Path To Extend To Boston|url=http://www.wbur.org/2014/04/30/somerville-bike-path-extension|accessdate=3 May 2014|newspaper=WBUR|date=30 April 2014}}</ref> Officials had contemplated abandoning the path portion of the GLX in order to save costs, but after hiring new management, a contractor agreed to the parallel path while still cutting costs.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Gallery of views along the bikeway==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"140px\">\nBedford Depot Park.jpg|Bedford Depot Park, with old B&M [[Budd Rail Diesel Car|RDC]]\nMinuteman Bikeway in Bedford, August 2007.jpg|In Bedford, near Wiggins Avenue\nFile:Minuteman Bikeway at the Lexington Depot, MA.jpg|Lexington Depot\nFile:Spy pond arlington massachusetts 050322.jpg|Spy Pond, Arlington\nFile:Snow minuteman bike path arlington massachusetts 050322.jpg|Snow on the path, Arlington\nFile:Minuteman Bikeway, Cambridge.jpg|In Cambridge, near [[Alewife (MBTA station)|Alewife station]] and the junction with the [[Fitchburg Cutoff Path]]\nFile:AlewifeBikeParking.agr.2001.JPG|Bike parking at Alewife station\nFile:Trail connector along Alewife Station Access Road, February 2010.jpg|Connector to [[Cambridge Linear Park]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Minutemen]]\n*[[Uncle Sam Memorial Statue]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.minutemanbikeway.org/ Minuteman Bikeway - official website]\n*[http://www.traillink.com/ViewTrail.aspx?AcctID=6015981 Minuteman Commuter Bikeway] | Rails-to-Trails Conservancy\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gJT5jHMQ420&list=PLTOf_IkJHwrgEgU8y_Q4YFX74FqvBh_88 Video | Virtual cycling video of the Minuteman Bikeway] (2012)\n*[https://vimeo.com/322717980 Video | \"The Minuteman Trail, America\u2019s 500th Rail\"] (1993)\n*[http://www.folb.net/ Friends of Lexington Bikeways]\n*[http://oldroads.com/minuteman.html Railroad maps from the 1870s show the right-of-way of what now the Minuteman Bikeway] \n\n[[Category:Bike paths in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Rail trails in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Lexington, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Bedford, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Arlington, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Bay Circuit Trail]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "AlgaeGraphix", "label": "safe", "comment": "RDT", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minuteman_Bikeway"}
{"title_page": "Arab states of the Persian Gulf", "text_new": "{{rewrite|date=June 2018}}<!---------\n  Note: Please see the talk page before changing \"Persian Gulf\" to \"Arab\" or \"Arabian Gulf\".\n ---------->\n[[File:Arab_Gulf_States_english.png|thumbnail|260px|The [[Persian Gulf]]'s coastline skirts seven Arab countries on its western shores and [[Iran]] to the east. ([[Oman]]'s [[Musandam peninsula]] meets the Persian gulf at the [[Strait of Hormuz]])]]\n\nThe '''Arab states of the Persian Gulf''' are the seven [[Arab world|Arab states]] which border the [[Arabian Gulf]], namely [[Bahrain]], [[Kuwait]], [[Iraq]], [[Oman]], [[Qatar]], [[Saudi Arabia]] and the [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE).<ref>{{cite book |author1=Mary Ann T\u00e9treault |author2=Gwenn Okruhlik |author3=Andrzej Kapiszewski |title=Political Change in the Arab Gulf States: Stuck in Transition |url=https://www.rienner.com/title/Political_Change_in_the_Arab_Gulf_States_Stuck_in_Transition |quote=The authors first focus on the politics of seven Gulf states: Bahrain, Iraq, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and the UAE. |year=2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xIJBiLdNJm4C&pg=PP55&dq |title=World Migration 2005 Costs and Benefits of International Migration |publisher=International Organization for Migration |page=53 |year=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Official to Tour Arabian Gulf Arab Lands |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/05/05/world/us-official-to-tour-persian-gulf-arab-lands.html |quote=A leading American diplomat will start a trip to Iraq and six other Arab countries of the Persian Gulf region this week to discuss the Iran-Iraq war, Administration officials said today. |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |year=1987}}</ref> All of these nations except Iraq are part of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gcc-sg.org/en-us/Pages/default.aspx|title=\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0644\u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0648\u0646 \u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|website=www.gcc-sg.org}}</ref> and prefer to use the term \"[[Persian Gulf naming dispute|Arabian Gulf]]\" rather than the historical name of the [[Persian Gulf]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Henderson|first1=Simon|title=Understanding the Gulf States|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/understanding-the-gulf-states|website=The Washington Institute|accessdate=1 June 2016|date=Spring 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nSome states are [[constitutional monarchies]] with elected parliaments. [[Bahrain]] (''[[National Assembly (Bahrain)|Majlis al Watani]]'') and [[Kuwait]] (''[[National Assembly (Kuwait)|Majlis al Ummah]]'') have legislatures with members elected by the population.\n\nThe Sultanate of Oman also has an advisory council (''Majlis ash-Shura'') that is popularly elected. In the UAE, a federation of seven monarchical emirates, the [[Federal National Council (United Arab Emirates)]] functions only as an advisory body, but some of its members are now chosen via a limited [[electoral college]] nominated by the seven rulers. Saudi Arabia remains a [[hereditary monarchy]] with limited political representation. In Qatar, an elected national parliament has been mooted and is written into the new constitution, but elections are yet to be held.<ref>Gerd Nonneman, \"Political Reform in the Gulf Monarchies: From Liberalisation to Democratisation? A Comparative Perspective\", in Anoushiravan Ehteshami and Steven Wright (eds.)(2007), ''Reform in the Middle East Oil Monarchies'', {{ISBN|978-0-86372-323-0}}, pp. 3-45.</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n{{Main article|Culture of Eastern Arabia|Arab cuisine of the Persian Gulf}}\n\nSoap operas are important national pastimes in the Gulf Arab region. They are most popular during the time of [[Ramadan]], when families gather to break their fast. Most of these soap operas are based in [[Kuwait]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.broadcastprome.com/content-creation/big-plans-for-small-screens/#.VwhXXvl97IV|title=Big plans for small screens|work=BroadcastPro Me|quote=Around 90% of Khaleeji productions take place in Kuwait.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Constantinos |last= Papavassilopoulos|url=https://technology.ihs.com/496709/osn-targets-new-markets-by-enriching-its-arabic-content-offering|title=OSN targets new markets by enriching its Arabic content offering|work=[[IHS Inc.]]|date=10 April 2014}}</ref> Kuwaiti soap operas are the most-watched soap operas in the Persian Gulf region.<ref name=\"fattah\">{{cite news |first=Nawara |last=Fattahova |url=http://news.kuwaittimes.net/first-kuwaiti-horror-movie-to-be-set-in-haunted-palace-chilling-news-for-film-buffs/|title=First Kuwaiti horror movie to be set in \u2018haunted\u2019 palace|newspaper=Kuwait Times|date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Fahad|last=Al Mukrashi|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/oman/omanis-turn-their-backs-on-local-dramas-1.1568086|title=Omanis turn their backs on local dramas|newspaper=Gulf News|date=22 August 2015|quote=Kuwait\u2019s drama industry tops other Gulf drama as it has very prominent actors and actresses, enough scripts and budgets, produces fifteen serials annually at least.}}</ref> Although usually performed in the Kuwaiti dialect, they have been shown with success as far away as [[Tunisia]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Peter |last=Mansfield |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uzy_AAAAIAAJ&q|title=Kuwait: vanguard of the Gulf |publisher=Hutchinson |date=1990 |page=113 |quote=Some Kuwaiti soap operas have become extremely popular and, although they are usually performed in the Kuwaiti dialect, they have been shown with success as far away as Tunisia.}}</ref> Kuwaiti [[popular culture]], in the form of theatre, radio and television soap opera, flourishes and is exported to neighbouring Arab states of the Persian Gulf.<ref name=\"cliv\">{{cite book|author=Clive Holes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8E0Rr1xY4TQC&pg=PA75|title=Modern Arabic: Structures, Functions, and Varieties|date=2004|page=75|publisher=Georgetown University Press|isbn=978-1-58901-022-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Ali Alawi|url=http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/features/alis-roadtrip-from-bahrain-to-kuwait-photos_13423|title=Ali's roadtrip from Bahrain to Kuwait (PHOTOS)|quote=The trip to Kuwait \u2013 a country that has built a deep connection with people in the Persian Gulf thanks to its significant drama productions in theater, television, and even music \u2013 started with 25 kilometers of spectacular sea view}}</ref> Darb El Zalag, Khalti Gmasha, and Ruqayya wa Sabika are among the most important television productions in the Persian Gulf region.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theasian.asia/archives/87665|title=Kuwaiti Drama Museum: formulating thoughts of the Gulf|date=23 May 2014}}</ref> Kuwait is widely considered the cultural capital of the Arab states of the Persian Gulf region,<ref name=\"mdt\">{{cite news|url=http://www.muscatdaily.com/Archive/Features/Kuwait-an-urban-spectacle-3xlc|title=Kuwait an urban spectacle|work=[[Muscat Daily]]|date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljarida.com/articles/1461965247680716900/|title= \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647\u2026 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0643 \u064a\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a|work=[[Al-Jarida]]|language=Arabic|date=28 July 2011}}</ref> frequently dubbed the \"[[Hollywood]] of the Gulf\" due to the popularity of its Arabic television soap operas and theatre.{{refn|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mbc.net/ar/programs/banat-sokkar-nabat/articles/%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%85-%D8%AD%D8%B3%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%AD%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89--%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC----%D9%88%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%B1%D8%A3-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%82%D9%88%D9%82-%D9%81%D9%8A--%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%B3%D9%83%D8%B1-%D9%86%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%AA-.html|title=\u0645\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 \u062a\u0631\u062d\u0644 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \"\u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c\".. \u0648\u062a\u062a\u0628\u0631\u0623 \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0642\u0648\u0642 \u0641\u064a \"\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a \u0633\u0643\u0631 \u0646\u0628\u0627\u062a\"|work=[[Middle East Broadcasting Center|MBC]]|language=Arabic|date=29 August 2015|access-date=3 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011010019/http://www.mbc.net/ar/programs/banat-sokkar-nabat/articles/%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%85-%D8%AD%D8%B3%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%AD%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89--%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC----%D9%88%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%B1%D8%A3-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%82%D9%88%D9%82-%D9%81%D9%8A--%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%B3%D9%83%D8%B1-%D9%86%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%AA-.html|archive-date=11 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.alwatanvoice.com/arabic/news/2015/07/08/740666.html|title=\u0647\u064a\u0641\u0627\u0621 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 : \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0647\u064a \u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c|language=Arabic|date=8 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elfann.com/news/show/1059017/%D9%85%D9%86%D9%89-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%84%D9%88%D8%B4%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AA-%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC-%D9%88%D9%8A%D9%82%D8%B5%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%B4%D9%87%D8%B1%D8%A9|title=\u0645\u0646\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0644\u0648\u0634\u064a: \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0647\u064a \u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c \u0648\u064a\u0642\u0635\u062f\u0648\u0646\u0647\u0627 \u0644\u0644\u0634\u0647\u0631\u0629 |language=Arabic|date=25 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.alsharq.net.sa/2014/12/21/1267694|title=\u0627\u0631\u062d\u0645\u0629 \u0644\u0640 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0631\u0642: \u0623\u0628\u062d\u062b \u062f\u0627\u0626\u0645\u0627\u064b \u0639\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0645\u064a\u0651\u0632 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c|language=Arabic|date=21 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\"\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u064a\u0645 \u0644\u0640 \u00ab\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u064a\": \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0631\u0627\u0645\u0627 \u0645\u0646\u062a\u0639\u0634\u0629 ... \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u00ab\u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c |newspaper=[[Al Rai (Kuwaiti newspaper)|Al Rai]] |url=http://www.alraimedia.com/ar/article/celebrities/2016/02/03/654281/nr/kuwait |language=ar |date=3 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.alanba.com.kw/ar/art-news/8250/28-02-2007-%D8%B2%D9%8A%D9%86%D8%A8-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B3%D9%83%D8%B1%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AA-%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC/|title=\u0632\u064a\u0646\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0633\u0643\u0631\u064a: \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c|language=Arabic|date=28 February 2007|work=[[Al-Anba (Kuwait)|Al-Anba]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zYvv0hrk5mc|title=\u0627\u0644\u0646\u062c\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u0645\u064a\u062f\u064a \u062f\u0627\u0648\u0648\u062f \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c \u063a\u0635\u0628 \u0639\u0646 \u062e\u0634\u0645 \u0623\u0643\u0628\u0631 \u0631\u0623\u0633|work=Scope|date=26 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.alkhaleej.ae/alkhaleej/page/917342a7-6375-425a-97cb-d5f158adaee3|title= \"\u0623\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0633\u0645\u064a: \u0639\u0627\u062a\u0628 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u00ab\u062f\u0628\u064a\" \u0648\u00ab\u0623\u0645 \u0628\u064a \u0633\u064a|work=[[Al Khaleej (newspaper)|Al Khaleej]]|language=Arabic|date=3 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://alwatan.kuwait.tt/articledetails.aspx?id=184422&yearquarter=20122|title=!\u0637\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062f\u0631 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0648\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629: \u0627\u0646\u062c\u0630\u0627\u0628\u064a \u0644\u0640\"\u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c\"..\u0623\u0642\u062f\u0627\u0631|work=[[Al-Watan (Kuwait)|Al Watan]]|language=Arabic|date=4 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljarida.com/articles/1465215410991517600/|title=\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u0623\u0631\u062d\u0645\u0629: \u062d\u0631\u064a\u0635\u0629 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u062e\u062a\u064a\u0627\u0631 \u0646\u0635\u0648\u0635 \u062c\u064a\u062f\u0629 \u0623\u0643\u062b\u0631 \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0638\u0647\u0648\u0631 \u0641\u064a \u0631\u0645\u0636\u0627\u0646|work=[[Al-Jarida]]|language=Arabic|date=7 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.alqabas.com/Articles.aspx?ArticleID=480748&date=06062016&isauthor=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713142822/http://archive.alqabas.com/Articles.aspx?ArticleID=480748&date=06062016&isauthor=1|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 July 2016|title=\u0648\u0641\u0627\u0621 \u0645\u0643\u064a: \u0645\u0648\u0632\u0629 \u062a\u0639\u064a\u0634 \u0641\u064a \u0630\u0627\u0643\u0631\u062a\u064a|language=Arabic|work=[[Al-Qabas]]|date=13 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljarida.com/articles/1461795846058196900/|title=\u0645\u064a \u0623\u062d\u0645\u062f: \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0627\u0647\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0627\u0628\u0629 \u0644\u0627 \u062a\u0642\u0644\u0651\u0651 \u0631\u0642\u064a\u0627\u064b \u0639\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0631|language=Arabic|work=[[Al-Jarida]]|date=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://almada.cc/?p=100094|title=\u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a\u064a \u0623\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0645\u064a\u0633: \u0644\u0646 \u0623\u0646\u0633\u0649 \u0645\u0627 \u0641\u0639\u0644\u0647 \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u064a \u0645\u0639\u064a! |language=Arabic|date=6 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.alqabas.com/Articles.aspx?ArticleID=1119586&CatID=835|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911092840/http://archive.alqabas.com/Articles.aspx?ArticleID=1119586&CatID=835|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 September 2016|title=\u0633\u0646\u0627\u0621: \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c|language=Arabic|date=17 December 2015|work=[[Al-Qabas]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://alwatan.kuwait.tt/articledetails.aspx?id=429890&yearquarter=20152|title=\u0641\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0648 - \u0631\u0626\u064a\u0633 \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633 \u0625\u062f\u0627\u0631\u0629 \u0646\u0642\u0627\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a\u064a\u0629 \u062f. \u0646\u0628\u064a\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u064a\u0644\u0643\u0627\u0648\u064a: \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \"\u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c\" \u0644\u0643\u0646\u0647\u0627 \u0644\u0627\u062a\u0645\u0644\u0643 \u0623\u0643\u0627\u062f\u064a\u0645\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0644\u0641\u0646\u0648\u0646|language=Arabic|date=22 April 2015|work=Al Watan}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.annaharkw.com/annahar/Article.aspx?id=661706&date=05062016|title=\u0641\u0627\u064a\u0632 \u0628\u0646 \u062f\u0645\u062e: \u0646\u0641\u062e\u0631 \u0628\u0627\u0633\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0631 \u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f |language=Arabic|date=1 June 2016|work=[[Annahar (Kuwait)|Annahar]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.alanba.com.kw/ar/art-news/402315/12-08-2013-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%B1-%D8%B9%D9%8A%D8%B3%D9%89-%D9%84%D9%80-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D8%A3%D8%AA%D9%85%D9%86%D9%89-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D9%85%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A7%D8%AA%D9%8A-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AA%D9%8A%D8%A9/|title=\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0631\u062f\u0646\u064a\u0629 \u0639\u0628\u064a\u0631 \u0639\u064a\u0633\u0649 \u0644\u0640 \"\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u0628\u0627\u0621\": \u0623\u062a\u0645\u0646\u0649 \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0631 \u0645\u0634\u0627\u0631\u0643\u0627\u062a\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0631\u0627\u0645\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a\u064a\u0629|work=[[Al-Anba (Kuwait)|Al Anba]]|language=Arabic|date=12 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticlePrintPage.aspx?id=2478560&language=ar|title=Kuwait Cultural Days kick off in Seoul|work=[[Kuwait News Agency]]|language=Arabic|date=18 December 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nThe inhabitants of [[Eastern Arabia|Eastern Arabia's coast]] share similar cultures and music styles such as [[fijiri]], [[sawt (music)|sawt]] and [[liwa (music)|liwa]]. The most noticeable cultural trait of Eastern Arabia's Arabs is their [[Seafaring|orientation and focus towards the sea]].<ref name=\"an\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hsU798UPaeYC&pg=PA67&dq|title=Iranians in Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates|work=Eric Andrew McCoy|pages=67\u201368}}</ref> [[Sea|Maritime]]-focused life in the small Arab states has resulted in a [[Seafaring|sea-oriented society]] where livelihoods have traditionally been earned in marine industries.<ref name=\"an\"/>\n\nBefore the [[Cooperation Council for the Arab States of the Gulf|GCC was formed in 1981]], the term \"Khaleeji\" was solely used to refer to the [[Eastern Arabia#Population|inhabitants of Eastern Arabia]].<ref name=\"east\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dEC9AAAAIAAJ&q|title=Eastern Arabia Historic Photographs: Kuwait, 1900-1936|year=1986|work=Ahmad Mustafa Abu-Hakima}}</ref> Historically, \"Khaleeji\" meant descendants of [[Ichthyophagi]], the [[coast|coast-dwelling]] \"fish eaters\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ncfIAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA12&dq|title=The Persian Gulf in History |work=Lawrence G. Potter|pages=12}}</ref> Geographically, the Arabic-speaking is solely [[Eastern Arabia]].<ref name=\"ara\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v_FtAAAAMAAJ&q|title=History of eastern Arabia, 1750-1800: the rise and development of Bahrain and Kuwait|year=1965|work=Ahmad Mustafa Abu-Hakima}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F1pjGwAACAAJ&dq|title=Labor, Nationalism and Imperialism in Eastern Arabia: Britain, the Shaikhs and the Gulf Oil Workers in Bahrain, Kuwait and Qatar, 1932-1956|year=1991|work=Hassan Mohammed Abdulla Saleh}}</ref>\n\n== Freedom of press ==\nPress in the Arab states of the Persian Gulf have varying degrees of freedom with Kuwait topping the league with a lively press that enjoys considerably more freedom than its Persian Gulf counterparts according to [[Freedom House]] and [[Reporters Without Borders]]. Both organizations rank Kuwait's press as the most free of all Arab states of the Persian Gulf and, in fact, rank amongst the top three most free press in the Arab world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-press/freedom-press-2016|title=Freedom of the Press 2016|date=April 26, 2016|website=freedomhouse.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=2016 World Press Freedom Index |url=https://rsf.org/en/ranking# |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214174449/https://rsf.org/en/ranking |archivedate=2017-02-14 }}</ref> Qatar and Oman come in second and third respectively within the regional ranks.\n\n== Peace ==\nThe six Arab states of the Persian Gulf lie in a volatile region and their six governments, with varying degrees of success and effort, try and advance peace in their own countries and other countries. However, Arab countries in the Persian Gulf region - specifically Saudi Arabia and Qatar - stand accused of funding Islamist militants such as [[Hamas]] and the [[Muslim Brotherhood]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/qatar-four-middle-eastern-powers-cut-diplomatic-ties-terror-links-bahrain-egypt-saudi-arabia-uae-a7772836.html|title=Four huge Middle Eastern powers just cut ties with Qatar over 'terrorism' links|date=June 5, 2017|website=The Independent}}</ref> According to the Institute of Economics and Peace (IEP)'s Global Peace Index of 2016, the six governments had varying degrees of success in maintaining peace amongst their respective borders with Qatar ranked number 1 amongst its regional peers as the most peaceful regional and Middle Eastern nation (and ranked 34 worldwide) while Kuwait ranks second in both the regional and the Middle East region (and 51 worldwide) followed by the UAE in the third spot (61 worldwide).<ref>{{Cite news |title=Global Peace Index 2016 |url=http://www.visionofhumanity.org/sites/default/files/GPI%202016%20Report_2.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615041315/http://www.visionofhumanity.org/sites/default/files/GPI%202016%20Report_2.pdf |archivedate=2016-06-15 }}</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Gulf Cooperation Council.svg|thumbnail|260px|Map of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]]'s members (Iraq is not a member).]]\n\nAll of these Arab states have significant revenues from petroleum. The [[United Arab Emirates]] has been successfully [[Economy of UAE|diversifying the economy]]. 79% of UAE's [[GDP|total GDP]] comes from non-oil sectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/diversification-raises-non-oil-share-of-uaes-gdp-to-71-1.795268|title=Diversification raises non-oil share of UAE's GDP to 71%|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref> Oil accounts for only 2% of Dubai's GDP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.gulfjobsmarket.com/oil-makes-up-2-of-dubai-gdp-post-diversification-7861765-news|title=Oil Makes Up 2% of Dubai GDP Post-Diversification - Gulf Jobs News}}</ref> Bahrain has the Persian Gulf's first \"post-oil\" economy because the Bahraini economy does not rely on oil.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Bahrain: Reform-Promise and Reality|url=http://www.jepeterson.net/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderfiles/Peterson_Bahrain_Reforms.pdf|publisher=J.E. Peterson|page=157}}</ref> Since the late 20th century, Bahrain has heavily invested in the [[banking]] and [[tourism]] sectors.<ref name=EDB>{{Cite web|title=Bahrain's economy praised for diversity and sustainability |url=http://www.bahrainedb.com/EDBInBahrain.aspx?id=2134 |publisher=Bahrain Economic Development Board |accessdate=24 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228154653/http://www.bahrainedb.com/EDBInBahrain.aspx?id=2134 |archivedate=December 28, 2010 }}</ref>  The country's capital, [[Manama]] is home to many large financial structures. Bahrain and Kuwait have a high [[Human Development Index]] (worldwide rank of 45 and 48 respectively) and was recognised by the [[World Bank]] as [[high income economies]].\n\nIn addition, the small coastal states (especially Bahrain and Kuwait) were successful centers of trade and commerce prior to oil. Eastern Arabia also had significant pearl banks, but the pearling industry collapsed in the 1930s after the development of [[cultured pearl]] methods by Japanese scientists.{{cn|date=June 2018}}\n\nAccording to the [[World Bank]], most of these Arab states have been the world's most generous donors of aid as a share of GDP.<ref>{{cite web |title=The haves and the have-nots |url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2013/07/11/the-haves-and-the-have-nots |website=The Economist |date=11 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Persian Gulf naming dispute]]\n* [[Arabian Peninsula]]\n* [[List of Rulers of the Arab States of the Persian Gulf]]\n* [[Iran-Arab relations]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qEus420fcbgC&printsec=frontcover&dq | title=Transnational Connections and the Arab Gulf|year=2005 | editor=[[Madawi Al-Rasheed]]}}\n*{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0230618456| title=The Persian Gulf in History |year=2009 | editor=Lawrence G. Potter}}\n*{{cite book | url=https://www.amazon.com/Sectarian-Politics-Persian-Lawrence-Potter/dp/1849043388| title=Sectarian Politics in the Persian Gulf|year=2014| editor=Lawrence G. Potter}}\n* \"The Persian Gulf's ancient [[ethnic diversity|Ethnic Diversity]]: An Evolutionary History\" in ''[https://www.amazon.com/Security-Persian-Gulf-Obstacles-Consensus/dp/0312239505 Security in the Persian Gulf: Origins, Obstacles and the Search for Consensus]'', Edited by G. Sick and L. Potter, pp.&nbsp;284.\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://gulf2000.columbia.edu/ Gulf2000]\n*[http://www.grc.ae/ Gulf Research Center]\n\n{{Articles Related to Persian Gulf}}\n\n[[Category:Arabian Peninsula]]\n[[Category:Persian Gulf]]\n[[Category:Arab League]]\n", "text_old": "{{rewrite|date=June 2018}}<!---------\n  Note: Please see the talk page before changing \"Persian Gulf\" to \"Arab\" or \"Arabian Gulf\".\n ---------->\n[[File:Arab_Gulf_States_english.png|thumbnail|260px|The [[Persian Gulf]]'s coastline skirts seven Arab countries on its western shores and [[Iran]] to the east. ([[Oman]]'s [[Musandam peninsula]] meets the Persian gulf at the [[Strait of Hormuz]])]]\n\nThe '''Arab states of the Persian Gulf''' are the seven [[Arab world|Arab states]] which border the [[Persian Gulf]], namely [[Bahrain]], [[Kuwait]], [[Iraq]], [[Oman]], [[Qatar]], [[Saudi Arabia]] and the [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE).<ref>{{cite book |author1=Mary Ann T\u00e9treault |author2=Gwenn Okruhlik |author3=Andrzej Kapiszewski |title=Political Change in the Arab Gulf States: Stuck in Transition |url=https://www.rienner.com/title/Political_Change_in_the_Arab_Gulf_States_Stuck_in_Transition |quote=The authors first focus on the politics of seven Gulf states: Bahrain, Iraq, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and the UAE. |year=2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xIJBiLdNJm4C&pg=PP55&dq |title=World Migration 2005 Costs and Benefits of International Migration |publisher=International Organization for Migration |page=53 |year=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Official to Tour Persian Gulf Arab Lands |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/05/05/world/us-official-to-tour-persian-gulf-arab-lands.html |quote=A leading American diplomat will start a trip to Iraq and six other Arab countries of the Persian Gulf region this week to discuss the Iran-Iraq war, Administration officials said today. |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |year=1987}}</ref> All of these nations except Iraq are part of the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] (GCC),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gcc-sg.org/en-us/Pages/default.aspx|title=\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0644\u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0648\u0646 \u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|website=www.gcc-sg.org}}</ref> and prefer to use the term \"[[Persian Gulf naming dispute|Arabian Gulf]]\" rather than the historical name of the [[Persian Gulf]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Henderson|first1=Simon|title=Understanding the Gulf States|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/understanding-the-gulf-states|website=The Washington Institute|accessdate=1 June 2016|date=Spring 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nSome states are [[constitutional monarchies]] with elected parliaments. [[Bahrain]] (''[[National Assembly (Bahrain)|Majlis al Watani]]'') and [[Kuwait]] (''[[National Assembly (Kuwait)|Majlis al Ummah]]'') have legislatures with members elected by the population.\n\nThe Sultanate of Oman also has an advisory council (''Majlis ash-Shura'') that is popularly elected. In the UAE, a federation of seven monarchical emirates, the [[Federal National Council (United Arab Emirates)]] functions only as an advisory body, but some of its members are now chosen via a limited [[electoral college]] nominated by the seven rulers. Saudi Arabia remains a [[hereditary monarchy]] with limited political representation. In Qatar, an elected national parliament has been mooted and is written into the new constitution, but elections are yet to be held.<ref>Gerd Nonneman, \"Political Reform in the Gulf Monarchies: From Liberalisation to Democratisation? A Comparative Perspective\", in Anoushiravan Ehteshami and Steven Wright (eds.)(2007), ''Reform in the Middle East Oil Monarchies'', {{ISBN|978-0-86372-323-0}}, pp. 3-45.</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n{{Main article|Culture of Eastern Arabia|Arab cuisine of the Persian Gulf}}\n\nSoap operas are important national pastimes in the Gulf Arab region. They are most popular during the time of [[Ramadan]], when families gather to break their fast. Most of these soap operas are based in [[Kuwait]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.broadcastprome.com/content-creation/big-plans-for-small-screens/#.VwhXXvl97IV|title=Big plans for small screens|work=BroadcastPro Me|quote=Around 90% of Khaleeji productions take place in Kuwait.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Constantinos |last= Papavassilopoulos|url=https://technology.ihs.com/496709/osn-targets-new-markets-by-enriching-its-arabic-content-offering|title=OSN targets new markets by enriching its Arabic content offering|work=[[IHS Inc.]]|date=10 April 2014}}</ref> Kuwaiti soap operas are the most-watched soap operas in the Persian Gulf region.<ref name=\"fattah\">{{cite news |first=Nawara |last=Fattahova |url=http://news.kuwaittimes.net/first-kuwaiti-horror-movie-to-be-set-in-haunted-palace-chilling-news-for-film-buffs/|title=First Kuwaiti horror movie to be set in \u2018haunted\u2019 palace|newspaper=Kuwait Times|date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Fahad|last=Al Mukrashi|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/oman/omanis-turn-their-backs-on-local-dramas-1.1568086|title=Omanis turn their backs on local dramas|newspaper=Gulf News|date=22 August 2015|quote=Kuwait\u2019s drama industry tops other Gulf drama as it has very prominent actors and actresses, enough scripts and budgets, produces fifteen serials annually at least.}}</ref> Although usually performed in the Kuwaiti dialect, they have been shown with success as far away as [[Tunisia]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Peter |last=Mansfield |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uzy_AAAAIAAJ&q|title=Kuwait: vanguard of the Gulf |publisher=Hutchinson |date=1990 |page=113 |quote=Some Kuwaiti soap operas have become extremely popular and, although they are usually performed in the Kuwaiti dialect, they have been shown with success as far away as Tunisia.}}</ref> Kuwaiti [[popular culture]], in the form of theatre, radio and television soap opera, flourishes and is exported to neighbouring Arab states of the Persian Gulf.<ref name=\"cliv\">{{cite book|author=Clive Holes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8E0Rr1xY4TQC&pg=PA75|title=Modern Arabic: Structures, Functions, and Varieties|date=2004|page=75|publisher=Georgetown University Press|isbn=978-1-58901-022-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Ali Alawi|url=http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/features/alis-roadtrip-from-bahrain-to-kuwait-photos_13423|title=Ali's roadtrip from Bahrain to Kuwait (PHOTOS)|quote=The trip to Kuwait \u2013 a country that has built a deep connection with people in the Persian Gulf thanks to its significant drama productions in theater, television, and even music \u2013 started with 25 kilometers of spectacular sea view}}</ref> Darb El Zalag, Khalti Gmasha, and Ruqayya wa Sabika are among the most important television productions in the Persian Gulf region.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theasian.asia/archives/87665|title=Kuwaiti Drama Museum: formulating thoughts of the Gulf|date=23 May 2014}}</ref> Kuwait is widely considered the cultural capital of the Arab states of the Persian Gulf region,<ref name=\"mdt\">{{cite news|url=http://www.muscatdaily.com/Archive/Features/Kuwait-an-urban-spectacle-3xlc|title=Kuwait an urban spectacle|work=[[Muscat Daily]]|date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljarida.com/articles/1461965247680716900/|title= \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647\u2026 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0643 \u064a\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a|work=[[Al-Jarida]]|language=Arabic|date=28 July 2011}}</ref> frequently dubbed the \"[[Hollywood]] of the Gulf\" due to the popularity of its Arabic television soap operas and theatre.{{refn|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mbc.net/ar/programs/banat-sokkar-nabat/articles/%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%85-%D8%AD%D8%B3%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%AD%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89--%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC----%D9%88%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%B1%D8%A3-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%82%D9%88%D9%82-%D9%81%D9%8A--%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%B3%D9%83%D8%B1-%D9%86%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%AA-.html|title=\u0645\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 \u062a\u0631\u062d\u0644 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \"\u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c\".. \u0648\u062a\u062a\u0628\u0631\u0623 \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0642\u0648\u0642 \u0641\u064a \"\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a \u0633\u0643\u0631 \u0646\u0628\u0627\u062a\"|work=[[Middle East Broadcasting Center|MBC]]|language=Arabic|date=29 August 2015|access-date=3 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011010019/http://www.mbc.net/ar/programs/banat-sokkar-nabat/articles/%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%85-%D8%AD%D8%B3%D9%8A%D9%86-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%AD%D9%84-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89--%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC----%D9%88%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%B1%D8%A3-%D9%85%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%82%D9%88%D9%82-%D9%81%D9%8A--%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%B3%D9%83%D8%B1-%D9%86%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%AA-.html|archive-date=11 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.alwatanvoice.com/arabic/news/2015/07/08/740666.html|title=\u0647\u064a\u0641\u0627\u0621 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646 : \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0647\u064a \u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c|language=Arabic|date=8 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elfann.com/news/show/1059017/%D9%85%D9%86%D9%89-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%84%D9%88%D8%B4%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AA-%D9%87%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AE%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AC-%D9%88%D9%8A%D9%82%D8%B5%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%84%D8%B4%D9%87%D8%B1%D8%A9|title=\u0645\u0646\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0644\u0648\u0634\u064a: \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0647\u064a \u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c \u0648\u064a\u0642\u0635\u062f\u0648\u0646\u0647\u0627 \u0644\u0644\u0634\u0647\u0631\u0629 |language=Arabic|date=25 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.alsharq.net.sa/2014/12/21/1267694|title=\u0627\u0631\u062d\u0645\u0629 \u0644\u0640 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0631\u0642: \u0623\u0628\u062d\u062b \u062f\u0627\u0626\u0645\u0627\u064b \u0639\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0645\u064a\u0651\u0632 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0647\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c|language=Arabic|date=21 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\"\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u064a\u0645 \u0644\u0640 \u00ab\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u064a\": \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0631\u0627\u